{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"367ce0ba-4c2d-4108-a064-c56c7c5348b2","content":"Each file hits a different C# 13 breaking change. Here's the breakdown and fixes:\n\n---\n\n**1. Buffer.cs — `[InlineArray]` banned on `record struct`**\n\nC# 13 disallows `[InlineArray]` on record structs because the synthesized `Equals`/`GetHashCode` only compare the first element, silently producing incorrect behavior. Fix: use a plain `struct`.\n\n```csharp\n[System.Runtime.CompilerServices.InlineArray(10)]\nstruct Buffer\n{\n    private int _element0;\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n**2. Generator.cs — `unsafe` context now flows into iterators**\n\nIn C# 12, `unsafe` on the class was *ignored* for iterator methods, so the local function was treated as a standalone method that could `stackalloc`. C# 13 lifts the restriction on `unsafe` in iterators, meaning `unsafe` now *propagates in*, and `stackalloc` inside a local function of an iterator is disallowed. Fix: extract the local function to a regular method.\n\n```csharp\nunsafe class DataGenerator\n{\n    IEnumerable<int> Generate()\n    {\n        yield return 1;\n        Process();\n    }\n\n    private void Process()\n    {\n        int* p = stackalloc int[10];\n        // ... work with pointer\n    }\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n**3. Resolver.cs — First-class span types change overload resolution**\n\nC# 13 introduces first-class span conversions at the language level. The empty collection expression `[]` now converts equally well to both `ReadOnlySpan<int>` and `Span<object>`, making the call **ambiguous**. Fix: disambiguate with an explicit cast.\n\n```csharp\nclass Resolver\n{\n    static void Process(ReadOnlySpan<int> ros) {}\n    static void Process(Span<object> s) {}\n\n    static void Main()\n    {\n        Process((ReadOnlySpan<int>)[]);\n    }\n}\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"3a491a54-d860-4656-ac57-08d827d6f0c8","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about C# 13 / .NET 9 breaking changes. Let me reason through each case based on my knowledge of C# 13 language changes.\n\n1. **Buffer.cs** - `InlineArray` on a `record struct`: C# 13 disallows `[InlineArray]` on `record struct` types. In C# 12, this was allowed but could produce incorrect behavior (e.g., the synthesized `Equals`/`GetHashCode` only considered the first element). C# 13 makes this a compiler error. Fix: change `record struct` to `struct`.\n\n\n2. **Generator.cs** - `stackalloc` in unsafe context within iterator: In C# 12, you could use `stackalloc` in a local function nested inside an iterator method, as long as the local function itself wasn't an iterator. The compiler would hoist the iterator state machine while keeping the local function with `stackalloc` intact. C# 13 likely tightened this rule and now disallows `stackalloc` in any context reachable from an iterator method. The local function `Process()` with `stackalloc` inside an iterator is the issue—in C# 12 it worked because local functions were compiled separately, but C# 13 tightened the rules for how unsafe operations in local functions are treated when they're nested inside iterators. Let me think through this more carefully. reconsider the actual C# 13 breaking changes:\n\n1. **InlineArray on record struct** - This is definitely a C# 13 breaking change. `[InlineArray]` attribute is no longer allowed on record structs. Fix: use plain `struct`.\n\n2. **stackalloc in local function in iterator** - The breaking change here is that C# 13 now allows `unsafe` context to propagate into iterator methods, whereas previously it didn't. This means a local function inside an iterator now inherits the unsafe context from the class declaration, and since `stackalloc` isn't permitted in iterators regardless, the code fails. The solution is to extract the local function as a separate static method outside the iterator.\n\n3. **Resolver.cs** - Looking at the `Process([])` overload resolution issue, in C# 12 the empty collection expression `[]` preferred `ReadOnlySpan<int>`, but in C# 13 this resolution behavior may have changed, causing ambiguity between `ReadOnlySpan<int>` and `Span<object>`. So the core issue is that C# 13's first-class span types make `[]` ambiguous when multiple overloads accept different span types—previously the compiler had a preference, but now both `ReadOnlySpan<int>` and `Span<object>` are equally valid targets. The workaround is to explicitly specify the type or cast the collection expression to remove the ambiguity.\n\nNow I'm organizing the breaking changes by category, starting with the `[InlineArray]` attribute restriction on record structs. Now I'm providing the corrected code samples for each of these three issues.","outputTokens":2496},"id":"254c8e5f-4894-445d-a3e9-a962c22e8be7","timestamp":"2026-04-08T01:14:55.983Z","parentId":"7fa50542-f729-4cbe-8de9-7a4339cd8813"}
